<p>I’m Renaud, currently working at <a href="https://fr.getaround.com/">Getaround</a> in the Product &amp; Engineering team where I contribute to building a car-sharing service to change the way we use cars. Here on <a href="/blog">the Blog page</a>, you can find some blog posts I wrote on various topics related to my work and my learnings.</p>

<p>If you want to learn more about me, check out the <a href="/about">About</a> page or you can contact me via <a href="https://twitter.com/_renaudb">Twitter</a>, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/rboulard/">Linkedin</a> or using email <em>boulard.renaud-at-gmail-dot-com</em>, I’m open to chat on topics related to dev/product/tech or new work opportunities, I will get back to you within 24 hours.</p>

<p>In the meantime some quotes and resources that I’d like to share with you on software development and product development:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Ask open-ended questions instead of making strong or opinionated statements. <cite>Gergely Orosz</cite> — <a href="https://stackoverflow.blog/2019/09/30/how-to-make-good-code-reviews-better/">How to make good code reviews better</a> <strong>#CodeReview</strong></p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>The brain can only effectively process so much information at a time; beyond 400 lines of code, the ability to find defects diminishes. <cite>Smartbear</cite> — <a href="https://smartbear.com/learn/code-review/best-practices-for-peer-code-review/">Best Practices for Code Review</a> <strong>#CodeReview</strong></p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>Our driving philosophy is the belief that critiques should be motivating, not intimidating. Helpful, not discouraging. <cite>Noah Levin</cite> — <a href="https://www.figma.com/blog/design-critiques-at-figma/">Design critiques at figma</a>  <strong>#DesignCritiques</strong></p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p><a href="https://ethics.org.au/ethics-explainer-the-sunlight-test/">The Sunlight Test</a> – where you test your intentions by asking if you’d do what you were doing if the whole world was watching. <cite>Matthew Beard</cite> — <a href="https://www.atlassian.com/blog/technology/ethical-design-in-tech">Ethical design in tech</a></p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>Meetings suddenly can become a productive forum for creation instead of one-to-many broadcasting. <cite>David Gasca</cite> — <a href="https://medium.com/swlh/the-silent-meeting-manifesto-v1-189e9e3487eb">The Silent Meeting Manifesto v1</a></p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>At the end, did I do it, or didn’t do it, YES NO it’s simple no judgment in it <cite> Andy Grove</cite> <a href="https://www.facebook.com/whatmatterscom/videos/andy-grove-teaching-okrs-in-the-70s-at-intel/458914971197411/">Andy Grove teaching OKRs in the 70s at Intel</a></p>
</blockquote>

<p><em>Renaud</em></p>
